article.description: Becky Hammon made three 3-pointers and scored 15 points to lead the New York Liberty to a surprisingly easy 73-63 victory Friday night at Sacramento.
article.headline: Monarchs suffer just second home loss of season
article.linkText: Liberty catch Monarchs off-guard in Sacramento
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Playing the second of back-to-back
road games, the New York Liberty didn't look the slightest bit
tired.

Becky Hammon made three 3-pointers and scored 15 points to lead
the Liberty to a surprisingly easy 73-63 victory Friday night over
the Sacramento Monarchs.

It was the second road win in as many nights for the Liberty
(10-9), who moved past Washington into second place in the Eastern
Conference. New York won 80-70 at Phoenix on Thursday night.

New York converted 8-of-15 3-point attempts and shot 56 percent
overall in winning in Sacramento for the first time since June 19,
2001.

"They hit every shot they could possible hit and we had hands
in their face," Sacramento center Yolanda Griffith said. "And we
couldn't make anything."

No kidding. The Monarchs missed their first 10 shots, made just
5-for-24 in the opening half and shot 37 percent overall.

The loss was only the second at home this year for the Monarchs
(13-7), who are now 7-2 at Arco Arena. The Western
Conference-leading Monarchs have lost two straight games for the
first time this season.

"We came in and we did a terrific job of executing," New York
coach Pat Coyle said. "We really did a good job on the boards
after being embarrassed at home (in a 61-50 loss to Sacramento)."

Ann Wauters was a solid inside presence for the Liberty, scoring
13 points. Vickie Johnson had 12 points and Crystal Robinson added
10.

Griffith scored 18 points for Sacramento and Kara Lawson had 10.

Ahead by 10 points, New York started the second half with a 15-6
run. A 3-pointer by Hammon put the Liberty ahead 45-26 at the 14:05
mark and the Monarchs didn't get the lead below double figures the
rest of the game.

"It was a great performance, a team effort," Johnson said.
"We came out and were very focused. It was a great win,
back-to-back wins."

Benefiting from Sacramento's anemic offense, the Liberty led
30-20 at the half.

Sacramento's leading scorer, DeMya Walker, did not suit up for
the game after spraining her right knee Thursday in practice.
Walker, who scored 20 points and had eight rebounds in an earlier
win over the Liberty, is expected to be out two to three weeks.

"That's huge, she (Walker) is huge for them," Coyle said.
"She's so athletic that she wreaks havoc on the defensive end."
